BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Kearsley Home Furnishings Moving Sale
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T173000
UID:260406j7_8Coe3EkSDH7jFEa6x4A
DESCRIPTION:Kearsley\, Sonoma’s renowned luxury linen and textile atelie
 r\, is relocating. In preparation\, the atelier has released its Kearsley 
 and Barbara Beckmann inventory at rare\, decisive pricing\, beginning at 5
 0% off.\n\nThe sale includes in-stock bed linens\, duvet covers\, coverlet
 s\, sheets\, pillowcases\, shams\, and outdoor pillows\, as well as fine f
 abrics by the yard for upholstery and drapery. Also available are hotel sa
 mple robes\, antique furniture\, a sleigh bed\, original artwork\, and rar
 e textile pieces seldom offered to the public.\n\nA broader selection is a
 vailable in-store\, including one-of-a-kind furnishings and collector-leve
 l pieces not listed online.\n\nKearsley is located through the Orchard Pla
 ce driveway entrance at Winery Sixteen 600\, and can also be accessed dire
 ctly from First Street West. The atelier is situated upstairs\, in the bac
 k of the beautiful yellow building.\n\nThis is a limited opportunity to ac
 quire exceptional design work from one of Sonoma’s most distinctive atel
 iers. Ideal for interior designers\, private clients\, collectors\, and th
 ose seeking truly special gifts.\n\nIn-store at 561 First Street West\, So
 noma\, and online at kearsleyhome.com April 1 through April 17\, while sel
 ections last.
LOCATION:Kearsley Sonoma Atelier
URL:https://kearsleyhome.com/collections/moving-sale
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Unearthed Offerings Opening Reception
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T200000
UID:260403PFzpYoQ840uVi6VcZ38cKQ
DESCRIPTION:Opening reception: Friday\, April 10\, 5-8 PM. Light refreshme
 nts served\n\nExhibition hours: Saturday\, April 11 and 18\, noon to 4 PM\
 , or by appointment\n\nUnearthed Offerings brings together the work of S
 elena Wells and Erin FitzGerald in a shared excavation of ritual and memor
 y. This exhibition presents a collection of ceramic works that spark the i
 magination and uncover alternate worlds—both wished for and imagined.\n\
 nThe show reveals pottery that feels at once primitive and precise: forms 
 that hold anger\, reverence\, humor\, and stillness. Visitors are invited 
 to enter as witness and wanderer\, to dig in as the work amuses and deligh
 ts\, energizes and enthralls. What emerges are not simply objects\, but in
 ner worlds shaped by instinct and devotion.\n\nWhat has been buried is bro
 ught forward. What is imagined becomes tangible. Each piece is an offering
 —a gesture toward unseen rites and personal mythologies.\n\nAbout the Ar
 tists\n\nErin FitzGerald Although Erin FitzGerald has worked for many year
 s as a painter and illustrator\, two years ago she began creating three-di
 mensional forms as an extension of her practice. Deeply drawn to the mediu
 m\, she now fully embraces clay as a primary material.\n\nIn today’s pol
 itical climate\, FitzGerald’s ceramic work often carries a social dimens
 ion\, what she describes as “political pottery” or “social cerami
 cs.” As a longtime activist and labor organizer\, she finds it natural 
 for some of her sculptures to move in this direction. Her ideas emerge as 
 she builds each piece\, while the construction itself is carefully plotted
  to ensure structural stability.\n\nAlongside sculptural work\, FitzGerald
  also creates smaller functional pieces infused with the energy she experi
 ences in herself and the world around her. Raw\, sometimes imprecise forms
  reveal the presence of the artist’s hand—bold\, direct\, and unapolog
 etic.\n\nSelena Wells Selena Wells began working in ceramics in 2024 after
  decades in other mediums. She quickly fell hard for clay and would spend 
 every free hour in the studio if life permitted.\n\nHer work centers on fi
 gures—none realistic\, all at least a little strange. Wells often aims f
 or a “just dug up” quality\, creating what she describes as “weird l
 ittle guys” that feel like artifacts from some adjacent world. These fig
 ures balance mystery with emotional familiarity\, inviting viewers to enco
 unter something both otherworldly and deeply human.
LOCATION:Vallejo Clay Workshop: Upstairs Gallery
URL:https://www.vallejoclay.com/event-details/opening-reception-for-uneart
 hed-offerings
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
