BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Cookbook Club
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T133000
UID:260303cgNZnM0dqUCM2wBuTrbkkQ
DESCRIPTION:Are you interested in trying new recipes or just wanting to ge
 t out of your cooking comfort zone? A cookbook book club blends the joy of
  reading with the creativity of cooking and the warmth of sharing meals. B
 rowse a selection of themed cookbooks every month\, then prepare and share
  your meals for the next meeting! February: French cuisine - A visit to Fr
 ance through classic culinary techniques and fresh\, modern influences. Fr
 om slow braises and buttery sauces to inventive new flavors inspired by gl
 obal ideas\, French cooking blends tradition and creativity in every bite.
  Together\, these methods make the cuisine vibrant\, evolving\, and undeni
 ably yummy. March: Pie/Pi Month - We will celebrate pies in every form! Fr
 om classic fruit pies and creamy custards to hearty pot pies\, empanadas\,
  samosas\, turnovers\, and galettes\, this month honors the creativity and
  comfort of foods encased in a crust. It's a tasty reminder that nearly ev
 ery culture has its own version of "pie\," and every one of them is worth 
 celebrating. April: SWANA - April marks Southwest Asian and North African 
 \\(SWANA\\) Heritage Month and Arab American Heritage Month. SWANA is an i
 nclusive\, decolonial geographic term that represents the diverse communit
 ies of Southwest Asia and North Africa\, including but not limited to Arab
  cultures. This month offers an opportunity to celebrate the region's rich
  culinary traditions-from aromatic spices and slow-cooked stews to vibrant
  mezze and sweets-highlighting food as a central expression of SWANA herit
 age. Plates\, cutlery\, and refreshments provided. Please be aware that di
 shes may contain or come into contact with common allergens\, such as dair
 y\, eggs\, wheat\, soybeans\, tree nuts\, peanuts\, fish\, or shellfish. I
 f you are interested in attending please contact Kate at Sonoma Valley Lib
 rary for more information. \\(707\\) 996-5217 kdeadder@sonomalibary.org
LOCATION:Sonoma Valley Library
URL:https://events.sonomalibrary.org/event/cookbook-club-103264
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Poetry Reading
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T153000
UID:260303DNSuylsv70WeHyg2OJQD-w
DESCRIPTION:Enjoy a live poetry reading with local poets Dave Seter\, Gwyn
 n O'Gara\, Shawna L. Swetech\, Bill Vartnaw\, and Kurt Schweigman. Each po
 et will share original work. There will be a Q&A after the reading. Poet B
 ios: Kurt Schweigman is an enrolled member of the Oglala Lakota Nation and
  was raised in the hardscrabble of a Rapid City\, SD urban Indian neighbor
 hood. He emerged on the spoken-word scene in the late 1990s\, winning seve
 ral poetry slam competitions throughout the United States and in Germany. 
 He is a self-taught writer and has been widely published. Kurt formerly pe
 rformed and published under the name Luke Warm Water for the first several
  years of his poetry journey. His most recent poetry collection is Conflue
 nces of Solitude \\(Mitote Press\, 2023\\). He is currently at work on his
  debut novel\, Sitting Bull in Rome. Shawna L. Swetech\, RN-a retired hosp
 ital medical/surgical nurse\, is a poet\, visual artist and integrative we
 llness coach. Her poems and art\, ranging from the personal to the politic
 al\, draw inspiration from the deep wells of human nature and the natural 
 world. Her poetry appears in various journals and anthologies\, including 
 Rattle\, The Healing Muse\, Ars Medica\, Pulse\, and the American Journal 
 of Nursing. She believes poetry and art are important healing medicines fo
 r the ills of our modern world\, and uses art and journaling in her integr
 ative Reiki and Flower Essence practice. Her first poetry collection based
  on her 35 year nursing career\, "Standing in Their Fire\," published by K
 elsay Books. Bill Vartnaw\, Sonoma County Poet Laureate \\(2012-13\\)\, wa
 s born and raised in Petaluma\, California. He is the author of two books 
 of poetry and four chapbooks. The most recent being The Nile to the Milky 
 Way. Bill is publisher of Taurean Horn Press\, started in San Francisco 50
 -odd years ago. He has been published in Beatitude\, North Coast Literary 
 Review\, Paterson Literary Review\, and Tule Review. Bill assisted Geri Di
 giorno with the Petaluma Poetry Walk from 1999 to sometime in the twenty-t
 eens when he became director. He handed off the Walk to Kary Hess in 2024.
  Gwynn O'Gara: At college she was lucky to study with Denise Levertov\, an
 d later the poet Herman Berlandt identified her as an "imagist." She worke
 d as a poet teacher with California Poet in the Schools for 26 years\, and
  from 2010-2011\, served as Sonoma County Poet Laureate. Along the way she
  performed with Rumi's Caravan\, and last year Ed Coletti entrusted her wi
 th producing the tri-annual Poetry Festival at Café Frida in Santa Rosa. 
 Published in Calyx\, Paddlefish\, and The Evansville Review. Gwynn's chapb
 ooks include Snake Woman Poems published by Beatitude Press\, Fixer-Upper 
 from dPress\, Winter at Green Haven from WordTemple Press\, Sea Cradles fr
 om the Occidental Center for the Arts\, and We Who Dream from Finishing Li
 ne Press. Dave Seter is an environmental engineer\, poet\, essayist\, and 
 translator. He is the author of the full length poetry collection Don't Si
 ng to Me of Electric Fences \\(Cherry Grove\, 2021\\). His new chapbook is
  Somewhere West of the Mississippi \\(Mammoth Publications\, 2025\\). He i
 s currently serving as Sonoma County Poet Laureate 2024-2026.
LOCATION:Northwest Santa Rosa Library
URL:https://events.sonomalibrary.org/event/poetry-reading-106400
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
