DESCRIPTION:Kearsley\, Sonoma’s renowned luxury linen and textile atelie
 r\, is relocating. In preparation\, the atelier has released its Kearsley 
 and Barbara Beckmann inventory at rare\, decisive pricing\, beginning at 5
 0% off.\n\nThe sale includes in-stock bed linens\, duvet covers\, coverlet
 s\, sheets\, pillowcases\, shams\, and outdoor pillows\, as well as fine f
 abrics by the yard for upholstery and drapery. Also available are hotel sa
 mple robes\, antique furniture\, a sleigh bed\, original artwork\, and rar
 e textile pieces seldom offered to the public.\n\nA broader selection is a
 vailable in-store\, including one-of-a-kind furnishings and collector-leve
 l pieces not listed online.\n\nKearsley is located through the Orchard Pla
 ce driveway entrance at Winery Sixteen 600\, and can also be accessed dire
 ctly from First Street West. The atelier is situated upstairs\, in the bac
 k of the beautiful yellow building.\n\nThis is a limited opportunity to ac
 quire exceptional design work from one of Sonoma’s most distinctive atel
 iers. Ideal for interior designers\, private clients\, collectors\, and th
 ose seeking truly special gifts.\n\nIn-store at 561 First Street West\, So
 noma\, and online at kearsleyhome.com April 1 through April 17\, while sel
 ections last.
LOCATION:Kearsley Sonoma Atelier
URL:https://kearsleyhome.com/collections/moving-sale
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Profs & Pints Napa: The Dirt on White-Collar Crime
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T203000
UID:260406IOYB9x44UkOzKQ3oPGmKbQ
DESCRIPTION:Profs and Pints Napa presents: “The Dirt on White-Collar Cr
 ime\,” a debunking of the myths and examination of the realities surrou
 nding “nonviolent\,” financially motivated misdeeds\, with Bryan Burto
 n\, associate professor of criminology and criminal justice at Sonoma Stat
 e University and researcher of white-collar crime\, corporate crime\, and 
 regulation.\n\nThe public’s understanding of white-collar crime is shape
 d less by empirical research than by powerful myths. Such myths distort ou
 r ideas about what constitutes normal or acceptable behavior as well as ou
 r assumptions about the harm caused by white-collar crime and our thoughts
  about who is responsible for it and how perpetrators should be held accou
 ntable.\n\nBe on hand as Bryan Burton\, a scholar of crime and criminal ju
 stice in the United States and abroad\, shines light on the reality surrou
 nding illegal misdeeds that get termed “white-collar.”  \n\nHe’ll 
 start by challenging an assumption that’s ingrained in the very definiti
 on of white-collar crime\, the idea that it’s somehow “nonviolent.” 
 We’ll look at how the unsafe consumer products\, hazardous workplaces\, 
 environmental contamination\, and corporate negligence associated with whi
 te-collar and corporate crime often result in serious injury\, illness\, a
 nd death.\n\nProfessor Burton also will debunk the myth that white-college
  crime is somehow less costly than conventional street crime\, showing how
  the financial and social costs of white-collar offenses often far exceed 
 those associated with conventional street offenses. \n\nHe’ll shatter t
 he notion that we can rely on regulatory agencies to protect us from serio
 us white-collar misdeeds\, describing how regulatory enforcement is hinder
 ed by political pressures and resource constraints. As part of this discus
 sion\, he’ll look at the phenomenon of regulatory capture\, when indepen
 dent watchdog agencies become overly influenced by\, and end up advancing 
 the interests of\, the industries or groups they were established to overs
 ee.\n\nFinally\, he’ll take on the cynical beliefs that nothing can be d
 one about white-collar crime or that white-collar offenders are somehow un
 touchable. He’ll explain why accountability for white-collar crime is of
 ten uneven.\n\nWe’ll look at practical ways that society\, organizations
 \, and audience members as individuals can work to fight white-collar crim
 e and reduce its harms. You’ll leave feeling wiser and more empowered to
  keep yourself from being victimized. \\(Tickets available only online. Ad
 vance tickets: $13.50 plus processing fees. Doors: $17\, or $15 with a stu
 dent ID. Doors open at 5:30 and the talk begins at 6:30.\\)\n\nImage by Ca
 nva
LOCATION:Napa Yard - Oxbow Gardens
URL:https://bohemian.com/events-calendar/#/details/profs-pints-napa-the-di
 rt-on-white-collar-crime/18512911/2026-04-14T18
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Tomatoes & Peppers: From Seedling to Harvest
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T180000
UID:2604019cPqfX0vvE2YkcqDpvtMfw
DESCRIPTION:Tomatoes & Peppers: From Seedling to Harvest\n\nLearn how to g
 row healthy\, productive tomato and pepper plants in your home garden. Thi
 s hands-on workshop covers the full growing cycle—from seedlings to tran
 splanting and seasonal care.\n\nIn this workshop you’ll:\n\n• Learn pl
 anting timelines and seedling care\n\n• Practice potting up young plants
 \n\n• Understand soil preparation and transplanting techniques\n\n• Ex
 plore irrigation\, fertility\, and plant maintenance\n\nEach participant w
 ill take home three tomato or pepper seedlings to grow and plant in their 
 own garden.
LOCATION:Gather Sebastopol
URL:https://bohemian.com/events-calendar/#/details/tomatoes-peppers-from-s
 eedling-to-harvest/18486303/2026-04-14T16
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:INTO THE LIGHT: Light-filled aintings by Katy Boggs
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T100000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T170000
UID:260330R8EOqF5RkkmKv4TnXtM1cg
DESCRIPTION:Katy's paintings are an exploration of light—how it shapes f
 orm\, reveals color\, and defines what we see.\n\n"I am drawn to moments w
 here light is felt as much as seen: filtering through dense leaves\, tower
 ing in the crowns of trees\, glinting off cresting waves\, or softening in
 to the quiet glow of a sunset. Light is everywhere\; without it\, there is
  no seeing. Beyond its physical presence\, it also carries a deeper resona
 nce as a symbol of hope. In a time of uncertainty\, this work seeks to bri
 ng light into the image\, both visually and metaphorically."\n\nReception:
  April 25\, 4 to 6 pm.
LOCATION:Sebastopol Gallery
URL:http://sebastopolgallery.com
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
